COVID related grant funding allows for us to offer free meals to ALL students enrolled in Heartland Community Schools. This program will start on Monday and continue through the end of December or until funding ends. A letter with specifics will be included in elementary student backpacks and announced to students in grades 7-12. A letter was sent to all parents via email earlier this morning.
If your child typically does not eat breakfast, but will now, please let us know so that we can anticipate participation numbers. Current debt does not go away, so please make sure to settle negative accounts soon.
Have a great weekend!

post_text:
Fall activities kick off this next week, but like everything else, it won't be like it used to be. The biggest change is that we have to limit the number of spectators due to the directed health measure in place.
Each player in volleyball and football received a number of tickets based upon our maximum limits. YOU MUST HAVE A "PURCHASE PERMIT" TO GAIN ENTRY INTO A CONTEST. PLEASE SHARE AND PASS THE WORD SO THAT WE DON'T HAVE TO TURN ANYONE AWAY AT THE GATE! These permits are available from the athletes and will need to be presented at the ticket gate the night of contest in order to purchase a ticket.
If you cannot obtain one of these permits, you may watch the game on the internet at Striv.tv. Thank you for your understanding and cooperation in our efforts to keep our kids safe, in school, and participating in extra-curricular activities!

post_text:
We are asking everyone's cooperation regarding visitations at the school. Unless you are asked to come to the school for an appointment, we would really appreciate no visitors at this time for the protection of our students and staff. IF it is necessary to visit the school, please call ahead and understand that we need you to check in at the office once granted entry.
We know there is much excitement the first day of school, but if you could take your pictures outside and not enter the building, it would be appreciated. All visitors to our building must wear a mask and have their temperatures taken.
Thank you for helping us get a good start to the school year!

post_text: We can't wait to see you on Thursday! Do you know the best way to remain in school, participate in activities, and allow us to stay open? Wear a mask whenever you are within 6 feet of another person. While wearing one is not mandatory, at this point, the health department has told us that if we do have a case in school, who was wearing a mask and who was not will make a big difference in deciding who may have to quarantine. Let's keep you and others safe and in school! We can do this!

post_text: We are looking forward to finally sending our seniors off with our graduation ceremony this Saturday, August 1st at 2:00 PM. Please note that due to safety restrictions, the general public may not attend the ceremony. Only those with a ticket from a graduate will be allowed admission. We are also strongly encouraging masks and ask that those that attend to not gather in the hallways, gym, or parking areas before or after the ceremony. We don't like it either, but it is necessary for us to keep everyone safe and in order to even hold a ceremony for the class of 2020. Thank you!

The United States Congress passed the Coronavirus Aid, Relief, And Economic Security (CARES) Act, which includes one-time relief funding for local school districts, intended to address challenges of providing education during the COVID-19 pandemic.

The Nebraska Department of Education is seeking feedback from all stakeholders to understand local needs as well as potential investments and supports. Please take a moment to complete this short survey, also available in Spanish.

https://nde.qualtrics.com/jfe/form/SV_efislqh4QDEA1KZ.

Additionally, please include this link with your communication to parents and families.

Deadline to complete this survey is Monday, May 11, 2020.

post_text: We were able to hand out 1250 breakfasts, 1250 lunches, and milk to our Heartland students in Henderson and Bradshaw today! A huge shoutout to Val and Matt Quiring, Michelle Goertzen, Sarah Goertzen, Anne Regier, Kim Hiebner, Tara Maltsberger, Lynn Hall, Dana and Les Reinke, Tim Carr, Roy Nunnenkamp, and Brad Best for such great teamwork today! Be well, everyone!
text: We were able to hand out 1250 breakfasts, 1250 lunches, and milk to our Heartland students in Henderson and Bradshaw today! A huge shoutout to Val and Matt Quiring, Michelle Goertzen, Sarah Goertzen, Anne Regier, Kim Hiebner, Tara Maltsberger, Lynn Hall, Dana and Les Reinke, Tim Carr, Roy Nunnenkamp, and Brad Best for such great teamwork today! Be well, everyone!

post_text: Good morning Heartland! Elementary packets are ready to be picked up by the school. Packets will be delivered to Bradshaw with lunches. We will use the same assembly line format for picking up lunches today from 11:30 to 12:30 in Henderson. We ask that you stay in your vehicle and follow the line stopping at all points in the circle drive. Elementary packets during this time will be handed to you in your vehicle by school staff. Have a great week!

Henderson Summer Ball Update!

We haven't forgotten about our summer program. However just like everything else right now, we have to remain on hold until we get the "safe to play."

â€¢ Tball will still go on, just not during the normal season.
â€¢ Regular ball will look a little different but we as a league plan on getting a full season in once it's safe too.
â€¢ Adult Softball league will go on.

We can't give you exact dates but we can say we miss you and look forward to playing baseball/softball soon!

We encourage you to practice throwing, catching, hitting during the time you are at home with your families.

We will update as soon as we are able to.

Thank you and stay safe!

On Monday, March 30, PK-6 grade students or parents may pick up new enrichment packets in the foyer area at the front entrance of the school for the coming week. Packets will be ready to be picked up each Monday after 8:30am.

We plan to recycle the manila folders each week. Please either bring a bag to place your paperwork in or use one that will be provided. After you have taken the materials out of the folder, please place it back into the classroom box that it was in. Remember, we do not want paperwork returned to school that has been completed at home.

Please note that this week you will need to look closely in the foyer area because many teachers have additional materials that need to be taken home. Itâ€™s important that you also look in this area for artwork and items that are in the lost and found. Artwork and lost and found items also pertain to 7-12 students.

We hope you are all doing well, staying home, healthy, washing hands and practicing social distancing. We miss you all. #bethedifference

post_text:
Another recommendation to help keep our communities safe - if you have travelled recently to California, the state of Washington, the New York City area, or overseas, please contact your physician before coming to or sending your children to school. They may recommend a 14-day self-quarantine to make sure you are healthy. A recent ski trip to Colorado may trigger the same recommendation.
Of course, we are concerned for our children but this virus is most dangerous if they pass it around and take it home to grandparents or those with other health issues.
As always, you as parents have the option of keeping your children home for safety reasons.
Letâ€™s work together and selflessly to keep each other healthy. Be well.

post_text:
Heartland will be in session tomorrow, Monday, March 16,2020. The district will continue to monitor the COVID-19 situation and make related decisions with the help of NDE, the governor, health officials such as the CDC, Nebraskaâ€™s Health Department, Four Corners Health Dept, and local medical professionals. We plan to stay open all week and re-evaluate the situation on Friday.
However, with the ever-changing landscape, we may need to make different plans much sooner. Information changes by the hour.
Parents, please make arrangements in case the school would be required to close for 2 weeks or as long as 8 weeks. Please do not come to the school if you exhibit symptoms of illness and continue the practices of good hand washing, covering coughs and sneezes, and not touching your face.

post_text: The American Mothers Association holds a 5th grade essay contest every year in coordination with their Mother Of the Year recognition. Over 160 essays were submitted across the state and evaluated by teachers belonging to the State English Teachersâ€™ Association. Out of those 160, 10 finalists were chosen to read their essays at the Capitol in Lincoln. This year, Madelyn Janzen was a top 10 finalist as well as the 1st place winner. Governor Pete Ricketts was present at the ceremony and invited Madelyn and her family, to have lunch at the Governorâ€™s Mansion. Madelynâ€™s essay is now entered in the national contest in Washington D.C. Congratulations Madelyn.
